a)|M\u00e9tis]] || 5,685 || {{Percentage | 5685 | 517887 | 1 }}\t\n|-\t\n| [[Inuit]] || 115 || {{Percentage | 115 | 517887 | 1 }}\t\n|-\t\n| colspan=2 | '''Total Aboriginal population''' || '''13,460''' || '''{{Percentage | 13460 | 517887 | 1 }}'''\t\n|-\t\n| colspan=2 | [[European Canadian|European]] || 200,365 || {{Percentage | 200365 | 517887 | 1 }}\t\n|-\t\n| colspan=2 | '''''Total population''''' || '''''517,887''''' || '''''100%'''''\t\n|}\n\n=== Religion ===\n\nThe 2011 National Household Survey states, \"71.4% of the population in Surrey reported a religious affiliation, while 28.6% said they had no religious affiliation. For British Columbia as a whole, 55.9% of the population reported a religious affiliation, while 44.1% had no religion.\n\nProportionally, Surrey has more Sikhs than any other Canadian city. The top three most reported religious affiliations in Surrey were [[Christianity]] (38.2%), [[Irreligion]] (28.6%) and [[Sikhism]] (22.6%). These were also the top three most frequently reported religions in British Columbia.<ref>2011 National Household Survey {{cite web|url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/as-sa/fogs-spg/Pages/FOG.cfm?lang%3DE%26level%3D4%26GeoCode%3D5915004#tabs1_2 |title=Archived copy |access-date=November 9, 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160601035038/https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/as-sa/fogs-spg/Pages/FOG.cfm?lang=E&level=4&GeoCode=5915004 |archive-date=June 1, 2016  }}</ref>\n\n=== Languages ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:darkGrey;\"\n! ''Mother tongue''\n! ''Population''\n! ''Percentage''\n|-\n| English\n| 247,685\n| 47.82%\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#efefef; color:black\"\n| [[Punjabi language|Punjabi]]\n| 106,100\n| 20.48%\n|- style=\"background:#efefef; color:black\"\n| [[Mandarin Chinese|Mandarin]]\n| 22,885\n| 4.42%\n|- style=\"background:#efefef; color:black\"\n| [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| 18,335\n| 3.54%\n|- style=\"background:#efefef; color:black\"\n| [[Tagalog language|Tagalog]]\n| 17,540\n| 3.39%\n|- style=\"background:#efefef; color:black\"\n| [[Korean language|Korean]]\n| 8,065\n| 1.56%\n|- style=\"background:#efefef; color:black\"\n| [[Cantonese]]\n| 7,095\n| 1.37%\n|- style=\"background:#efefef; color:black\"\n| [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n| 6,730\n| 1.29%\n|- style=\"background:#efefef; color:black\"\n| [[Vietnamese language|Vietnamese]]\n| 6,365\n| 1.23%\n|- style=\"background:#efefef; color:black\"\n| [[Arabic]]\n| 4,940\n| 0.95%\n|}\n{{Clear left}}\n\n=== Economic indicators ===\n\nAs of 2010, Surrey had the highest median family income of [[Canadian dollar|CDN$]]78,283, while BC provincial median was $71,660, and national's median was $74,540. The average family income was $85,765.<ref name=\"StatsCan\">{{cite web | url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=CSD&Code1=5915004&Data=Count&SearchText=Surrey&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=59&A1=All&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1 | title=NHS Profile, Surrey, CY, British Columbia, 2011 | publisher=StatsCan | date=2011 | accessdate=February 14, 2015}}</ref> South Surrey area had the highest average household income of all six town centres in Surrey, with an average of $86,824 as of 2010. Median household income was also high at $62,960.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.surrey.ca/files/health_profile_south_surrey.pdf | title=Community Profile 2010 | publisher=Fraser Health | accessdate=February 14, 2015}}</ref> South Surrey's neighbourhood of Rosemary Heights is the richest in Surrey and throughout the Metro Vancouver area, with a median income more than twice the regional average.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://vancouversun.com/Rosemary+Heights+Surrey+richest+place+Metro+Vancouver/6236922/story.html | title=Rosemary Heights in Surrey is richest place in Metro Vancouver | publisher=Vancouver Sun | date=March 1, 2012 | accessdate=February 14, 2015 | author=Chad Skelton}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2010, the median household income of Surrey was $67,702 (versus the national median of $76,437), where 29.4% of households in Surrey earned a household total income of $100,000 or more, which is above the national average of 25.9%.<ref name=\"StatsCan\"/><ref name=\"StatsCan\"/><ref name=\"National Survey\">{{cite web | url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Data=Count&SearchText=Canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=All&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1 | title=National Survey | publisher=StatsCan | accessdate=February 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\n\nThe city is characterized by low population density [[urban sprawl]], typical of North American cities, which includes areas of residential housing, light industry and commercial centres and is prone to strip development and malls. Approximately 35 percent of the land is designated as part of the [[Agricultural Land Reserve (British Columbia)|Agricultural Land Reserve]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} The city is mostly hills and flatland, with most of the flatland in Tynehead, Hazelmere, south of Cloverdale, and Colebrook.\n\n=== Climate ===\nThe climate is typically inter-coastal Pacific-Northwest: rainy, wet winters, often with heavy rainfall lasting into early spring, with mild, sunny summers and cool autumns.\n\n{{Weather box\n| location     = Surrey (1981\u22122010)\n| metric first = yes\n| single line  = yes\n| Jan record high C = 15.5\n| Feb record high C = 19.4\n| Mar record high C = 25.0\n| Apr record high C = 29.0\n| May record high C = 34.5\n| Jun record high C = 33.3\n| Jul record high C = 35.0\n| Aug record high C = 34.5\n| Sep record high C = 34.5\n| Oct record high C = 29.0\n| Nov record high C = 21.0\n| Dec record high C = 16.7\n| year record high C = 35.0\n| Jan high C = 6.7\n| Feb high C = 8.7\n| Mar high C = 11.7\n| Apr high C = 14.6\n| May high C = 17.9\n| Jun high C = 20.4\n| Jul high C = 23.1\n| Aug high C = 23.6\n| Sep high C = 20.9\n| Oct high C = 14.5\n| Nov high C = 8.7\n| Dec h