]''' and [[technology]] involved some significant events.\n\n==Astronomy==\n* [[Galileo Galilei]] publishes ''[[Letters on Sunspots]]'', the first major work on the topic.\n\n==Paleontology==\n* Bones, probably of an elephant, are found in France but at first interpreted to belong to a giant human.\n\n==Technology==\n* September 29 \u2013 The [[New River (England)|New River]] (engineered by Sir [[Hugh Myddelton]]) is opened to supply [[London]] with drinking water from [[Hertfordshire]].<ref name=\"Cassell's Chronology\">{{cite book|last=Williams|first=Hywel|title=Cassell's Chronology of World History|url=https://archive.org/details/cassellschronolo0000will/page/243|url-access=registration|location=London|publisher=Weidenfeld & Nicolson|year=2005|isbn=0-304-35730-8|pages=[https://archive.org/details/cassellschronolo0000will/page/243 243\u2013248]}}</ref>\n\n==Births==\n* September 25 \u2013 [[Claude Perrault]], [[French people|French]] [[architect]] and [[physicist]] (died [[1688 in science|1688]])\n\n==Deaths==\n* June 16 \u2013 [[Jakob Christmann]], [[German people|German]] [[Oriental studies|orientalist]] and [[astronomer]] (born [[1554 in science|1554]])\n* July 2 \u2013 [[Bartholomaeus Pitiscus]], German [[Trigonometry|trigonometrist]] (born [[1561 in science|1561]])\n* August 25 \u2013 [[David Gans]], [[German Jewish]] [[mathematician]] and astronomer (born [[1541 in science|1541]])\n* [[Mathew Baker]], [[English people|English]] [[shipwright]] (born [[1530 in science|1530]])\n* [[Johann Bauhin]], [[Swiss people|Swiss]] [[physician]] and [[botanist]] (born 1541)\n* [[Jacques Guillemeau]], French [[surgeon]] (born [[1550 in science|1550]])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:1613 in science]]\n[[Category:17th century in science]]\n[[Category:1610s in science]]\n", "name_user": "Chris j wood", "label": "safe", "comment": "dab", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1613_in_science"}
